# **Workflow Engine Document**

## **Summary**

workflow engine created for connecting our all microservices with rules which will define by system administrator or system developer. rules and flows can be define on all of system events that happen. modules or microservices can be register on workflow engine that we describe it later. we used workflow core open source project as engine base. we made many changes on many workflow core logic.
you can see workflow core docs [here](https://github.com/danielgerlag/workflow-core "here").

## **Software Architecture**

as you see in bellow image, all communications between workflow and system microservices are using RabbitMQ or Kafka. microservices events queued in message broker then workflow nodes will pick up it and if engine has be any workflow definition for it, create an instance from workflow and will run it.
also when workflow engine wants call a microservice, it queued a request on microservice message broker with unique job ID for processing the request by microservice. then the microservice pickup the request and after request processing put response in message broker with the same request job ID.

![struct](data:image/png;base64,)

we have two entry points in workflow engine project.
|Project|Description
|--|--|
| Server | REST service of workflow engine for managing and making workflow definitions and all another operations on workflows|
|Background Service| actually background service is our workflow node. primary workflows processes and decisions calculate and run from here. you can run this project multi times that each running instance called a node in our system.

Inside of background service architecture showed at bellow :

![inside-node](./nodes-detail.PNG)

As you see each background service represent a workflow engine node. each node needs **MongoDB** and **Redis** that we explained details of databases in some section later. and for communication with outside of node it will be need to message broker. also nodes speak together using system message broker **(Kafka & RabbitMQ)**.

Another internal application layers described here.

|Project|Description
|--|--|
|Abstraction Layer| all of models and enums and types that shared with all of layers defined here |
|Business Layer|all logical codes about workflows and business of workflow engine placed here|
|Data Access Layer| all related codes to data and communication with database placed here. for example database repository defined here. |

and finally the project layer structure showed at bellow:

![layer](data:image/png;base64,)

## **Databases**

### MongoDB Database

the workflow engine uses **MongoDB** for storing workflows and their details.
in workflow Database we have these collections :

1. **Workflow Definition**: we store all workflow definitions in this collection.
2. **Workflow**: stores all created instances of workflow. created instances mean workflow instances that be created from workflow definitions.
3. **Events**: stores all internal engine events.
4. **Subscriptions**: stores all event subscriptions.
5. **Execution_error**: stores all errors that happen in any levels of workflow instances.

### Redis Database

in the workflow engine we used redis database for storing three types key value collections.

1. workflow locking collection for locking workflows between running nodes.
2. caching workflow details
3. workflow internal queues for executing steps in order, etc...

### Business Layer

As we saw in project architucrure section, we have multi layer in our workflow engine. in this section we want to deep on layers. the most important layer that we need to explain it is **[MicroEthos.Workflow.Business](https://github.com/Dr-Ethos/MicroEthos.WF/tree/master/MicroEthos.Workflow.Business)** layer.

**Business Layer** has following directory structure :

![business_layer](./Business_layer.PNG)

So we going to explain it:

1. **Extensions** : Contains extensions of all types. for example we place string extesions methods file here.
2. **Providers** : Contains all client providers files **(REST,GRPC,TCP,etc...)**.
3. **Services** : Contains all business and logical workflow engine files. **(ModuleBiz.cs)**.
4. **Statics** : Contains all static files which we using them in all sections of our service.
5. **Workflow** : Contains all files that related to our [Our Base Workflow Engine](https://workflow-core.readthedocs.io/en/latest/).
6. **Statup.cs** : This file represents a method for registering types in service Dependency Injector and all things which related to **Business Layer First Loading**.

in workflow directory we have a **[StepMiddleware.cs](https://github.com/Dr-Ethos/MicroEthos.WF/blob/master/MicroEthos.Workflow.Business/Workflow/Steps/Middlewares/StepMiddleware.cs)** file. **in this file take workflow decisions and we can say, this file is most importance and most affect file in workflow engine node codes**.

Base Workflow Core that we used it, uses **[Dynamic Lambda](https://dynamic-linq.net)** for passing inputs and outputs and also in conditions in if and while nodes. this is good but when we want to run a workflow this operation per exchanging steps is very slow, so will be affected on workflow run performance.
one of our works in **[StepMiddleware.cs](https://github.com/Dr-Ethos/MicroEthos.WF/blob/master/MicroEthos.Workflow.Business/Workflow/Steps/Middlewares/StepMiddleware.cs)** is ignoring Dynamic Lambda Expression and using **JTI**. that is Javascript Compiler on C#. it is very fast, so in this file we resolved inputs, outputs and conditions expressions for nodes or actions.

Bellow code is a segment of **[StepMiddleware.cs](https://github.com/Dr-Ethos/MicroEthos.WF/blob/master/MicroEthos.Workflow.Business/Workflow/Steps/Middlewares/StepMiddleware.cs)** code for detecting and executing expression using **Regex** and **JTI (Javascript Compiler)** :

    private object? ResolveCurrentStepInput(string inputName, Type inputStepType, BsonValue value,
                    WorkflowStateModel stateModel, IStepExecutionContext context)
    {
        var state = stateModel.State;
        var replacedStatement = Regex.Replace(value.ToString()!, @"(\$\$[^\s.\$]+_[^\s.]+_Out)(\.[^\s\`\'\$""]+)?",
            match =>
            {
                var segments = match.Value.Trim('.').Split('.');
                JToken token = null;
                if (segments[0].Split('_').First().ToLower().Trim().StartsWith("$$foreach") &&
                    segments[0].Split('_')[1].ToLower().Trim() == "item" &&
                    !state.Items.Names.Contains(segments[0]))
                    token = JToken.Parse(context.Item?.ToString() ?? string.Empty);
                else if (state.Items.Names.Contains(segments[0]))
                    token = JToken.Parse(state.Items[segments[0]]?.ToString() ?? string.Empty);

                for (var i = 1; i < segments.Length; i++)
                    token = token?[segments[i][0].ToString().ToLower() + segments[i][1..]];

                if (token == null)
                    return "null";

                if (value.ToString()!.StartsWith("{") && token.Type == JTokenType.String)
                    return token.ToString().Replace("\"", "\\\"").Replace("\'", "\\\'");
                
                if (!value.ToString()!.StartsWith("{") && token.Type == JTokenType.String)
                    return $"\"{token.ToString().Replace("\"", "\\\"").Replace("\'", "\\\'")}\"";
                
                return token.ToString().ToLower();
            });
        replacedStatement = replacedStatement.Replace("`", "'");
        replacedStatement = replacedStatement.Replace("\"'null'\"", "null");

        if (replacedStatement.Trim().StartsWith("{") && replacedStatement.Trim().EndsWith("}"))
        {
            replacedStatement = Regex.Replace(replacedStatement, @":(\s+)?("")(.*)+("")", match =>
            {
                var cleanItem = match.Value.Trim(':').Trim().Trim('\"');
                var jsRes = Evaluator.Engine.Execute($"let result = {cleanItem};")
                    .GetValue("result");
                var evaluatedExpression = jsRes.ToObject().ToString();
                Evaluator.Engine.ResetCallStack();
                return jsRes.Type == Types.String ? $": 
                \"{evaluatedExpression!.Replace("\"", "\\\"").Replace("\'", "\\\'")}\"" : $": {evaluatedExpression}";
            });
            var parsed = JsonConvert.DeserializeObject(replacedStatement, inputStepType)!;
            return Convert(parsed, inputStepType);
        }
        else
        {
            var jsRes = Evaluator.Engine.Execute($"let result = {replacedStatement};")
                .GetValue("result");

            //evaluation for integers return number.0 (5.0) and must be convert to integer
            var evaluatedExpression = _jsonService.Serialize(jsRes.ToObject());
            context.ExecutionPointer.ExtensionAttributes[$"$${inputName}_In"] = evaluatedExpression;

            var inputTypeCode = Type.GetTypeCode(inputStepType);
            if (inputTypeCode is TypeCode.Int16 or TypeCode.Int32 or TypeCode.Int64 or TypeCode.Byte
                    or TypeCode.UInt16 or TypeCode.UInt32 or TypeCode.UInt64 ||
                (inputStepType.IsEnum && int.TryParse(evaluatedExpression, out var o)))
                evaluatedExpression = Regex.Replace(evaluatedExpression, @"\d+\.\d+", match =>
                {
                    var numberSplit = match.Value.Split(".");
                    if (System.Convert.ToInt32(numberSplit[1]) == 0)
                        return numberSplit[0];
                    return match.Value;
                });
            Evaluator.Engine.ResetCallStack();

            var parsed = JsonConvert.DeserializeObject(evaluatedExpression, inputStepType)!;
            return Convert(parsed, inputStepType);
        }
    }

We need to explain this method for better realization. so in workflow engin all conditions and main parameters bind as a input. for example in [IF Step or Node](https://workflow-core.readthedocs.io/en/latest/control-structures/#if-conditions) we have a **Condition expression** with string type. that is a string input in **IF Step**. and also we should have one output for all of actions in workflow engine.
If you see the method signiture, we have these parameters :

- **inputName** parameter that presents **Input Property Name**.
- **inputType** parameter that presents **Input Property Type** that we gave it using reflection.
- **value** a BsonValue parameter that presents **Value of property** that stores in **MongoDB**.
- **stateModel** parameter that presents **Shared State Model Between Steps**.
- **context** parameter that presents **Workflow Core Shared Context**.

Briefly this method gets microservice action input value as a **JSON expression** that can be a primitive type such as **string ==> "Test"**, **integer ==> 20** or can be complex object such as **{ name : "masoud"}**.
So lets talk about **JSON expression**. a **JSON expression** demonstrait a hardcoded JSON value or a JSON Object that it's properties bind with expression string. and this JSON Object will be create in **Workflow Engine Client App** then will be send to server.
We need this expression for binding output of one step or node to input of another step.

For example in below we have a JSON Expression :

    {
        age: "10 + $Step1_Out.User.Age",
        name: "$Step1_Out.User.Name",
        lastname: "10 + $Step1_Out.Lastname",
        description: "TEST HARD CODED"
    }

Imagine your second step model has **(age, name, lastname, description)** properties in its input model and we want to bind some of them with before step (step 1) and bind description property with hardcoded string. above JSON is **JSON Expression that present it**.

- **age** is a integer property that we bind it with sum of returned user age from Step 1 with 10.
- **name** and lastname are string propery that we bind it with returned user name and lastname from Step 1.
- **description** is a string propery that binded with hardcode string.

then JSON Expression that you see been compiled and evaluated then deseralize and assign to next step input with above method **ResolveCurrentStepInput(...)**.

Other sections of middleware follows [Our Base Workflow Core Middleware](https://workflow-core.readthedocs.io/en/latest/workflow-middleware/) structure and you can read for understanding.

The other thing that we implemented in business layer of workflow engine is ***[Steps](https://github.com/Dr-Ethos/MicroEthos.WF/tree/master/MicroEthos.Workflow.Business/Workflow/Steps)***. your workflow definition will make with steps that you want.
We have 2 step types:

1. ***Primitives Steps***: these step types are basic steps that you need them for create rules on your workflow definitions. these types provided by our base workflow core and you can see and follow them in [Control Structure Section](https://workflow-core.readthedocs.io/en/latest/control-structures/).
   - **If Step**
   - **Foreach Step**
   - **While Step**
   - **Schedule Step**

2. ***Normal Steps***: these steps are our logical steps and you can make your desired step in workflow engine in [Steps Directory](https://github.com/Dr-Ethos/MicroEthos.WF/tree/master/MicroEthos.Workflow.Business/Workflow/Steps).
In workflow engine we prepare these steps in two ways:
   - **HardCoded Steps**: you can create your steps like other steps in [Steps Directory](https://github.com/Dr-Ethos/MicroEthos.WF/tree/master/MicroEthos.Workflow.Business/Workflow/Steps). we have template for creating steps. see bellow step code.

          [StepModule("Core")]
          public class AddNumberStep : StepBodyAsync
          {
            [StepInput] public int Input1 { get; set; }

            [StepInput] public int Input2 { get; set; }

            [StepInput] public Response Input3 { get; set; }

            [StepOutput] public int Output { get; set; }

            public override async Task<ExecutionResult> RunAsync(IStepExecutionContext context)
            {
                Console.WriteLine("=====================> Started");
                //await Task.Delay(50000);
                // Thread.Sleep(50000);
                // Console.WriteLine($"==================> email with Title ({Input3.Title}) received ....");
                Output = Input1 + Input2;
                return ExecutionResult.Next();
            }
          }

   As you see in code we have **StepModule**, **StepInput**, **StepOutput** attributes that you need use them for creating your hardcoded steps. **StepModule** use for categorize your steps, for example this step is in *Core* category. also **StepInput**, **StepOutput** use for defining inputs and outputs of your steps. you need inherit from **StepBodyAsync Base Class** and implement RunAsync method. *RunAsync* method runs when receive your step turn in your running workflow so you need white you logical codes about the step in *RunAsync* method body.

   - **Auto Generated Steps**: these steps was generated when microservice sent register request to workflow. actually these steps are like harcoded steps just make dynamically with **Workflow Engine** using microservice input and output JSON schemas.

### BackgroundService Layer

We described about background service. actually background services have **nodes role**. we can run this layer ***how many times as you want***. so lets see internal directory structure:

Project Structure           |  Background Services Directory
:-------------------------:|:-------------------------:
![Project](./Background_layer_1.PNG)  |  ![BackServiceDirectory](./Background_layer_2.PNG)

In the left image you can see ***Background Service Layer Directories*** and in right image you can see ***Inside of ServiceWorkers Directory***.

- ***Background Service Layer Directories*** contains some simple files such as Statup.cs and Program.cs that we explained about them. you can see them in **Engine Directory**.

- ***Inside of ServiceWorkers Directory***: these are most important files in this layer. now we want explain about these background services. these service workers are using Message Broker (Kafka or RabbitMQ) in background and process all message brokers items. they are **heart of Workflow Engine Nodes**.

   1. **Workflow Module Service Worker**: this service worker is listening to all **Modules Events and Responses** with seperated **threads**. for each module(MicroService) was created one **thread**. also for listening to modules used message broker. in the bellow you can see main segment of this service worker.

          protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
          {
            try
            {
                LockObj.WaitOne();
                var modules = await LoadModules();
                await Initialize(stoppingToken);
                LockObj.Release();
                await Task.Delay(1000);
                
                while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
                {
                    var parallelCancelSource = new CancellationTokenSource();
                    var parallelCancellationToken = parallelCancelSource.Token;
                    Parallel.ForEachAsync(modules, async (module, cts) =>
                    {
                        // using var queueConnection = _kafkaConnectionFactory.Create("workflow");
                        using var queueConnection = _rabbitConnectionFactory.Create(string.Empty);
                        await _logger.Info(
                            $"Now listening on response of module {module.Name}({module.Version}) on queue {module.Queues.ResponseQueueName}.");
                        await _logger.Info(
                            $"Now listening on event of module {module.Name}({module.Version}) on queue {module.Queues.EventQueueName}.");
                        while (!parallelCancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested && !stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
                            try
                            {
                                var moduleResp = await queueConnection.Dequeue(module.Queues.ResponseQueueName, 50);
                                if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(moduleResp))
                                {
                                    var result = await _workflowListenerService.ModuleResponseReceived(moduleResp, module);
                                    if (result)
                                        await queueConnection.Ack(module.Queues.ResponseQueueName);
                                }

                                var moduleEvent = await queueConnection.Dequeue(module.Queues.EventQueueName, 50);
                                if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(moduleEvent))
                                {
                                    var result = await _workflowListenerService.ModuleEventRaised(moduleEvent, module);
                                    if (result)
                                        await queueConnection.Ack(module.Queues.EventQueueName);
                                }
                            }
                            catch (Exception e)
                            {
                                await _logger.Error("Error occured :", e);
                            }

                        await queueConnection.Close();
                    });

                    await Task.Delay(150000, stoppingToken);
                    parallelCancelSource.Cancel();
                    await Task.Delay(500, stoppingToken);
                }
            }
            catch (Exception e)
            {
                await _logger.Error("exception occured in workflow module listener background service ...", e);
            }
          }

   2. ***Workflow Runner Service Worker***: this service worker run the main engine and **listening to other nodes message**. for example **when a workflow definition created and ran or a module created then other nodes should be realize to load it in their scopes**. with this service worker nodes can be communicate with together. you can see main section of it's codes:

          protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
          {
            try
            {
                await Task.Delay(3000, stoppingToken);
                // WorkflowModuleServiceWorker.LockObj.WaitOne();
                // await WorkflowStarted(stoppingToken);
                // WorkflowModuleServiceWorker.LockObj.Release();

                await _logger.Info(
                    $"listening on new module created.");
                await _logger.Info(
                    $"listening on new workflow definition created.");
                // using var queueConnection = _kafkaConnectionFactory.Create(_nodeId);
                using var queueConnection = _rabbitConnectionFactory.Create("workflow");
                while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
                {
                    var createdModuleMsg = await queueConnection.Dequeue(TopicNames.WorkflowModuleCreated, 50);
                    if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(createdModuleMsg))
                    {
                        var createModuleRes = await ModuleCreated(createdModuleMsg);
                        if (createModuleRes)
                            await queueConnection.Ack(TopicNames.WorkflowModuleCreated);
                    }

                    var createdWorkflowDefMsg = await queueConnection.Dequeue(TopicNames.WorkflowDefinitionCreated, 50);
                    if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(createdWorkflowDefMsg))
                    {
                        var createWorkflowRes = await WorkflowDefinitionCreated(createdWorkflowDefMsg);
                        if (createWorkflowRes)
                            await queueConnection.Ack(TopicNames.WorkflowDefinitionCreated);
                    }

                    var workflowEventMsg =
                        await queueConnection.Dequeue(QueueHelper.GetNames(ModuleConstants.ModuleName).RequestQueueName,
                            50);
                    if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(workflowEventMsg))
                    {
                        var res = await WorkflowServeRequest(workflowEventMsg);
                        if (res)
                            await queueConnection.Ack(QueueHelper.GetNames(ModuleConstants.ModuleName).RequestQueueName);
                    }
                }
            }
            catch (Exception e)
            {
                await _logger.Error("exception occured in workflow runner background service ...", e);
            }
          }

   3. ***Terminate Running Workflow Instances***: this background service remove all workflow instances that could not finish completely after a specific time. this time can be change with administrator.

## **Microservices Communication with workflow engine**

workflow engine uses message brokers to communication with microservices.
brokers that support by workflow engine are Kafka and RabbitMQ.

- when you want to active Kafka message broker add this line:

        var kafkaHost = EnvironmentHelper.Get("KAFKA_HOST")!;
        var kafkaUsername = EnvironmentHelper.Get("KAFKA_USER_NAME")!;
        var kafkaPassword = EnvironmentHelper.Get("KAFKA_USER_PASS")!;


        services.AddKafkaConnectionPool(500);
        services.AddKafkaConnectionFactory(kafkaUsername, kafkaPassword, kafkaHost);
        services.AddKafka();

- when you want to active RabbitMQ message broker add this line:

        var rabbitHost = EnvironmentHelper.Get("RABBIT_SERVER")!;
        var rabbitUsername = EnvironmentHelper.Get("RABBIT_USERNAME")!;
        var rabbitPassword = EnvironmentHelper.Get("RABBIT_PASSWORD")!;
        
        services.AddRabbitConnectionFactory(true, rabbitUsername, rabbitPassword, rabbitHost);
        services.AddRabbit();
        services.AddRabbitConnectionPool(500, false, rabbitUsername, rabbitPassword, rabbitHost);

the workflow engine uses three types of topic for communicating with microservices using message broker that send to workflow when microservice wants register in workflow engine.

1. **requests topic**
2. **responses topic**
3. **events topic**

as a sample in our Omni Channel Microservice used this pattern:

**omnichannel-{request|response|event}-{prodoction|development}**
For example for development release of omni channel microservice events we used (omnichannel-event-development) topic or queue name.

Now we are going to explain how workflow engine and modules speak with message broker. we have 3 type of connections between MicroService and Workflow Engine.

1. **Workflow engine send request to module**: on module creation time, we generate dynamic codes for generating actions of module as workflow steps. these generated step codes use **[ModulesClient File](https://github.com/Dr-Ethos/MicroEthos.WF/blob/master/MicroEthos.Workflow.Business/Providers/ModulesClient.cs)** for calling corresponding MicroService action. this file has *Call Module* method to send a request messege in requests topic.

        public async Task<string> CallModule(string queueName, string moduleName,
            string stepName, object? inputPayload, WorkflowStateModel contextData)
        {
            var queueConnectionPool = (IPool<IQueueClient>) _serviceProvider.GetService(typeof(IPool<IQueueClient>))!;
            var payload = inputPayload == null
                ? new JObject().ToString()
                : JObject.FromObject(inputPayload).ToString();

            payload = BindServiceIdAndInstitutionIdWithReplacePayload(payload, contextData);
            inputPayload = JsonConvert.DeserializeObject(payload);
            
            var item = new
            {
                Command = stepName,
                ServiceId = contextData.ServiceId.ToString(),
                UserId = contextData.UserId.ToString(),
                InstitutionId = contextData.InstitutionId.ToString(),
                JobId = Guid.NewGuid().ToString(),
                TraceId = contextData.TraceId.ToString(),
                Payload = inputPayload,
                When = DateTime.UtcNow,
                ServiceName = ModuleConstants.ModuleName,
                RequireResponse = true
            };
            using (var connection = queueConnectionPool.Acquire())
            {
                await connection.Enqueue(queueName, _jsonService.Serialize(item));
            }

            await _logger.Info($"Called module ({moduleName}) action ({stepName}) with payload {payload} \n" +
                            $"TraceId is {item.TraceId} \n" +
                            $"JobId is {item.JobId}");

            return item.JobId;
        }

2. **Workflow engine receive response from module**: When Workflow Engine send a request to module, actually it create an internal event with request JobID and thread will be released until response with same JobID receive.

3. **Module raise an event to engine**: in this type engine listen to message broker until message comming.

Both of 2, 3 cases implemented in **[WorkflowModuleListenerService file](https://github.com/Dr-Ethos/MicroEthos.WF/blob/master/MicroEthos.Workflow.Business/Services/WorkflowModuleListenerService.cs)** and you can see it bellow:

    public async Task<bool> ModuleResponseReceived(string moduleResp, Modules module)
    {
        var moduleRespObj = _jsonService.Deserialize<WorkflowEventDto>(moduleResp);
        if (moduleRespObj == null ||
            string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(moduleRespObj.Command))
        {
            await _logger.Error("response of module received with invalid data");
            return true;
        }

        await _logger.Info(
            $"Response of module {moduleRespObj.ModuleId} and action {moduleRespObj.Command} received with payload {moduleRespObj.Payload}\n" +
            $"Job id is {moduleRespObj.JobId}\n" +
            $"Trace Id is {moduleRespObj.TraceId}");
        var payload = _jsonService.Serialize(moduleRespObj.Payload, SerializationType.CamelCase);
        await _workflowHost.PublishEvent(moduleRespObj.JobId, moduleRespObj.JobId, payload,
            DateTime.Now);
        return true;
    }

    public async Task<bool> ModuleEventRaised(string eventMsg, Modules module)
    {
        var eventMsgObj = _jsonService.Deserialize<WorkflowEventDto>(eventMsg);
        if (eventMsgObj == null ||
            string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(eventMsgObj.Command))
        {
            await _logger.Error("event received with invalid data");
            return true;
        }

        await _logger.Info(
            $"{eventMsgObj.Command} event raised from module {eventMsgObj.ModuleId} with payload {eventMsgObj.Payload}\n" +
            $"Job id is {eventMsgObj.JobId}");

        await using var scope = _serviceProvider.CreateAsyncScope();
        var runningWorkflows = await scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<IRepository<WorkflowDefinitions>>()
            .ListAsync(w => w.Status == WorkflowDefinitionStatus.Running); //&& w.Model.InstitutionId == eventMsgObj.InstitutionId && w.Model.ServiceId == eventMsgObj.ServiceId);

        var mustBeInitializeWorkflows = runningWorkflows.Where(w => w.Model.Steps.Count > 0
                                                                    && w.Model.Steps[0].StepType
                                                                        .Contains(module.AssemblyName) &&
                                                                    w.Model.Steps[0].StepType.ToLower()
                                                                        .Contains(eventMsgObj.Command.ToLower()))
            .ToList();

        var eventOutPropName = string.Empty;
        if (mustBeInitializeWorkflows.Count > 0)
        {
            var outProp = Utils.GetStepType(mustBeInitializeWorkflows.First().Model!.Steps.First().StepType)
                .GetProperties().FirstOrDefault(p => p.GetCustomAttributes(typeof(StepOutputAttribute)).Any());
            if (outProp == null)
                return true;
            eventOutPropName = outProp.Name;
        }

        foreach (var mustBeInitializeWorkflow in mustBeInitializeWorkflows)
        {
            mustBeInitializeWorkflow.RunParameters.Items[
                    $"$${mustBeInitializeWorkflow.Model!.Steps[0].Id}_{eventOutPropName}_Out"] =
                BsonValue.Create(_jsonService.Serialize(eventMsgObj.Payload));

            await _workflowHost.StartWorkflow(mustBeInitializeWorkflow.Model!.Id.ToString(),
                mustBeInitializeWorkflow.Model.Version, new WorkflowStateModel
                {
                    State = mustBeInitializeWorkflow.RunParameters,
                    TraceId = string.IsNullOrEmpty(eventMsgObj.TraceId) || 
                            eventMsgObj.TraceId == Guid.Empty.ToString() ? Guid.NewGuid() : new Guid(eventMsgObj.TraceId),
                    InstitutionId = new Guid(eventMsgObj.InstitutionId),
                    ServiceId = new Guid(eventMsgObj.ServiceId),
                    UserId = string.IsNullOrEmpty(eventMsgObj.UserId) ? null : new Guid(eventMsgObj.ServiceId)
                });
        }
        
        var payload = _jsonService.Serialize(eventMsgObj.Payload, SerializationType.CamelCase);
        await _workflowHost.PublishEvent(eventMsgObj.Command,
            module.Name, payload, DateTime.Now.AddSeconds(2));

        return true;
    }

## **Communication workflow engine nodes together**

As you saw, workflow engine can be run on multi node and you just need to run **[Engine Node Project](https://github.com/Dr-Ethos/MicroEthos.WF/tree/master/MicroEthos.Workflow.BackgroundService)** as many times as you want with bellow command in Background Service Project release directory :

    dotnet run ./MicroEthos.Workflow.BackgroundService.dll

We described about nodes communication in **[BackgroundService Layer](#backgroundservice-layer)**. nodes notify together with message broker (Kafka or RabbitMQ). for example when a module created **it will broadcast a message** to another nodes using message
broker then other nodes listen to workflow created module topic and receive message. so in the bellow code block one node process messages of other nodes. this code block is in **MicroEthos.Workflow.BackgroundService > ServiceWorkers > [WorkflowRunnerServiceWorker.cs](https://github.com/Dr-Ethos/MicroEthos.WF/blob/master/MicroEthos.Workflow.BackgroundService/ServiceWorkers/WorkflowRunnerServiceWorker.cs)** file.

        private async Task<bool> ModuleCreated(string moduleMsg)
        {
            try
            {
                await using var scope = _serviceProvider.CreateAsyncScope();
                var moduleService = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<IModuleService>();
                var module = _jsonService.Deserialize<Modules>(moduleMsg)!;
                await moduleService.Load(module.Name, module.Version, module.AssemblyFile);
                return true;
            }
            catch (Exception e)
            {
                await _logger.Error("error on module created event.", e);
                return false;
            }
        }

        private async Task<bool> WorkflowDefinitionCreated(string workflowDefMsg)
        {
            try
            {
                var workflowDef = _jsonService.Deserialize<WorkflowDefinitions>(workflowDefMsg);
                if (!_workflowHost.Registry.IsRegistered(workflowDef.Model.Id.ToString(), workflowDef.Model.Version))
                {
                    _workflowLoader.LoadDefinition(workflowDef.Raw, Deserializers.Json);
                }

                return true;
            }
            catch (Exception e)
            {
                await _logger.Error("error on workflow definition created event.", e);
                return false;
            }
        }

        private async Task<bool> WorkflowServeRequest(string req)
        {
            try
            {
                var request = _jsonService.Deserialize<WorkflowEventDto>(req);
                if (request == null)
                    return false;
                if (request.Command == ModuleRequests.ModuleRegistration)
                {
                    await using var scope = _serviceProvider.CreateAsyncScope();
                    var moduleService = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<IModuleService>();

                    var payload = _jsonService.Deserialize<WorkflowAddModuleModel>(_jsonService.Serialize(request.Payload));
                    var result = await moduleService.CreateAndLoadDynamically(payload);
                    if (result.Status != OperationResultType.Success)
                    {
                        return false;
                    }

                    await _logger.Info($"Module {payload.Name} successfully installed √√√√√");
                    return true;
                }

                return false;
            }
            catch (Exception e)
            {
                await _logger.Error("error on workflow request process ....", e);
                return false;
            }
        }

This methods recive messages from message broker then for processing the item, will pass to ***Business Layer Methods***.

## **Register Microservice or Module**

We have 2 options to register a microservice on workflow :

1. **with REST request to workflow engine server API**
2. **with message broker(Kafka & RabbitMQ) pushing message.**

for dotnet microservices we make a nuget package called [MicroEthos.Common.WF](https://github.com/Dr-Ethos/MicroEthos.Common/tree/master/MicroEthos.Common.WF). we used JSON schema standard for passing inputs and outputs throught workflow engine. so we used [NJSON Schema](https://github.com/RicoSuter/NJsonSchema) for generating inputs and outputs of microservice actions. if you want to register dotnet microservice in workflow engine you need add bellow code in your microservice startup file:

    var workflowQueues = QueueHelper.GetNames(WorkflowSharedConstants.ModuleName);
    var workflowModule = WorkflowModuleSchema.Generate(ModuleConstants.ModuleName);
    await using (var scope = serviceProvider.CreateAsyncScope())
    {
        await scope.ServiceProvider.GetService<IQueueClient>()!
            .Enqueue(
                workflowQueues.RequestQueueName,
                    new WorkflowEntityDto
                    {
                        Command = WorkflowSharedConstants.ModuleRegistration,
                        Payload = workflowModule
                    },
                    forceIdCheck: false
            );
    }

If your microservices don't write with dotnet and developed using another frameworks such as NodeJS or etc..., you need to call register module REST API. it's model give names of microservices and also inputs and outputs as a JSON Schema.

## **Unloading Module or Microservice**

Workflow engine allow you to unload your module or microservice with an REST API that you access it in [API References](https://workflow.microethos.com).

The importante thing in unloading your microservice is that shouldn't has any running workflow definition. if your module has active workflow definition you need stop the workflow definition that uses the module that you want to unload it then you can unlod it with [UNLOAD API](https://workflow.microethos.com)

the Unload REST Api has bellow signiture:

    [HttpPost(ModuleRoutes.ModuleUnload)]
    public async Task<OperationResult<bool>> UnloadModule(UnloadModuleRequest model)
    {
        return await _moduleService.Unload(model.Name, model.Version);
    }

## **Versioning**

Workflow engine supports registering microservices with multi version. register model take a version number as a parameter. by default it's value is 1 but you can increase it and send register request. **be carefule all of your microservices versions must be up**. so when you register the new version of your microservice then you can select it from workflow engine UI. you can see all actions of microservice with version number. so you can use it in your workflow definitions. in bellow we wrote our creating and versioning models. you can find these models and also other models in [Abstraction Layer](https://github.com/Dr-Ethos/MicroEthos.WF/tree/master/MicroEthos.Workflow.Abstraction).

    public class WorkflowDefinitionModel
    {
        public WorkflowDefinitionModel()
        {
            Steps = new List<WorkflowStepDefinitionModel>();
        }

        public Guid Id { get; set; }
        public string? InstitutionId { get; set; }
        public string? ServiceId { get; set; }
        public string Name { get; set; }
        public int Version { get; set; }
        public List<WorkflowStepDefinitionModel> Steps { get; set; }

        [BsonIgnore] public WorkflowAction? Action { get; set; }

        [BsonIgnore] public string MetaData { get; set; }
    }

    public class WorkflowStepDefinitionModel
    {
        public WorkflowStepDefinitionModel()
        {
            Inputs = new Dictionary<string, string>();
            Outputs = new Dictionary<string, string>();
            SelectNextStep = new Dictionary<string, string>();
            Do = new List<List<WorkflowStepDefinitionModel>>();
        }

        public string Id { get; set; }
        public string? Name { get; set; }
        public string StepType { get; set; }
        public string? NextStepId { get; set; }
        public Dictionary<string, string>? Inputs { get; set; }
        public Dictionary<string, string>? Outputs { get; set; }
        public Dictionary<string, string>? SelectNextStep { get; set; }
        public List<List<WorkflowStepDefinitionModel>>? Do { get; set; }
    }

In WorkflowDefinitionModel model you see the ***version property*** that you can change it for versioning.
